		<div class="title">Re: Ubuntu Unity</div>
	
	<div class="content">
		<blockquote class="restore">Another thing, I've rebound left-alt to tab as alt is rarely used in VIM and doing so allows me to use my thumb instead of my pinky for navigating autocompletion and ward off RSI.  Also, <a href="http://vimgolf.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://vimgolf.com/</a> is really cool regardless of whether you use emacs or vim or something else.  It's fun and wrinkles your brain while increasing your aptitude at a work skill.  Also Goladus, as someone who is primarily using Windows 7 for development atm I am finding using VIM (since it is focused on only succeeding at being a text editor) quite deficient when you are in a landscape where you do not have access to many exceptional utilities by default.  <br />
<br />
You can get around this fact in various ways using cygwin etc., but it's less than ideal still and quite a bear to do and due to some idiosyncracies with the windows command line, getting things like Vundle working in a vimrc is /weird/ and I have had to change a bunch of environment variables in windows to get it to realize I have certain programs installed like mlint and ack.  The reason the CLI wasteland is an issue over emacs in VIM is that it handicaps your ability to read output from commands into buffers, something that is essential.  Another thing, emacs has a sweet feature in slime that is replicated somewhat in VIM but it is only one-way in VIM and also there is not a tmux/screen terminal by default to use, which is what the slime plugin requires.  So, I think emacs is better if you are stuck in a windows environment for those reasons.<br />
<br />
Oh, another thing despite VIM's exceptional grammar and focus on having a sensible keybinding for a command and its inverse (such as p to put before a line, P to put after a line) such a concept does not exist by default with regard to transposing.  However, it's something that can be added somewhat easily with keybinding a sequence to a complex regex or grammar, which I mapped to [c ]c for characters, [w and ]w for words, [l and ]l for sentences, [&lt;space&gt; and ]&lt;space&gt; for adding new lines above or below lines.  Those keybinds were inspired due to the ]l, [l, [&lt;space&gt;, ]&lt;space mnemonic being put n by Tim Pope's unimpaired plugin though.<br />
<br />
Another area where emacs succeeds over VIM in usability/quickness is when it comes to interacting with files not in the current buffer via a macro/sequence of commands for performing some command on multiple files, especially those which are not loaded.  In Emacs it is pretty straightforward via using marks.  In VIM though instead of a 2 step process it is 2 to 3.  You first add those files as arguments,then add additional files potentially, and the use a separate command (argdo or bufdo depending on the context).  In the VIM context that adds up to a more bearish task.</blockquote>
	</div>
</li><li class="postbit blockbody" id="post_3">
	<div class="header">
		<div class="datetime">July 15th, 2012, 02:51 AM</div>
		<span class="username">Mihoko Ishii</span>
	</div>
	
	
		<div class="title">Re: Ubuntu Unity</div>
	
	<div class="content">
		<blockquote class="restore">Also, I will add that if you are suffering from insomnia that watching videos over text editors is a good solution.  One other layer of complexity in the VIM onion is the existence of multiple list buffers that are available and have a somewhat unique way of navigating the lists.  ATM I recall their being a quickfix list that contains compilation or syntax errors such as if you run a lint program on your code, a location list which remembers where you have been in a file so that you can quickly jump back or to a buffer and line and tab associated with a change in location or tag, a list of markers, registers, or command history.  Presently if seems like there is not a consistent grammar in terms of how these lists are utilized for navigation.  The quickfix list is what you will wind up explicitly using mostly though. The others are pretty transparent or only require remembering a couple of commands.  A list would probably be comparable to a ring in the emacs paradigm.<br />
<br />
The two editors really like stealing cool features from each other and other editors like Textmate for instance (bubbling text, snippets).  VIM's fugitive and surround has an emacs brother as an example, and VIM has imitators of dired and slime as well as the excellent easy motion that provides a visual method to jump to a location in a buffer in one to two strokes, very powerful.  Emacs slime has two-way communication with its Lisp though, where as the VIM slime's target isn't aware of the communicator and requires screen or tmux.  Emacs is a platform though where as VIM is a text editor as the saying goes. Sublime 2's fuzzy finder for docs is pretty interesting, not sure that it could work in the context of how VIM of emacs doc layout is done though <br />
 <br />
One more thing, a pro tip I received early on was to learn a few commands at a time using a post it note or whatever works for you, then move to some new info as you grasp the old mysteries so that you are more efficient and on the way to being a full on grey beard.  The low key amount of pop ups and animation and flashing appeals to me since it is much less distracting for myself like what writing on paper is instead of word.<br />
<br />
Additonally, if you use git and emacs or VIM, fugitive makes git stupidly easy/quick to use.  Combine that with snippets for ensuring your commit/bug comments are correctly stated (if you have some sort of keyword scheme used to indicate fixes) you have a pretty sleek work flow.  I'm pretty intoxicated from drinking the emacs/vim kool-aid at this point and don't even care.  It's like you discovers a unicorn that rode in on a rainbow and want to share the excitement with everyone. I'll probably delve into emacs hardcore next year as GNU software appeals to my inner nerd of yore and check out all the cool stuff it has like org mode.</blockquote>
	</div>
