		<div class="title">Re: Ubuntu Unity</div>
	
	<div class="content">
		<blockquote class="restore">After using emacs with evil for a while now, I must say that it is pretty gangster.  The learning curve goes from absurd to insane though as far as achieving deftness goes since evil requires knowing vi to make use of, and utilizing the emacs features requires knowing emacs.  What's sweet about the set up though is that you gain access to emacs lisp, multithreading, better integration with other gnu programs like gdb and gcc, and major modes like org mode that are brilliant.  I don't recommend that anyone do this, but I think it is state of the art as far as editors go due to combining the strengths of the emacs platform with vim's superior modal editing design and better micro-optimization of frequently used tasks.  Evil is pretty impressive though due to how rapidly the development has been.  The documentation for it is absolutely atrocious though and requires reading the source code to determine what commands are used so that you can rebind some things.  Like I said though, I don't recommend doing things this way for other humans.  I don't think that evil has a parallel to vim's autocommands though, which I used in vim for various things.  There is probably an emacsian way to achieve that however.  I think it's a shame that normal people who could benefit from well designed programs (not necessarily emacs or vim here) won't ever do so due to being unwilling to invest the time in learning them.  I use matlab/mathematica everyday but most people are stuck with calculators.</blockquote>
	</div>
