			<div class="message">After using emacs with evil for a while now, I must say that it is pretty gangster.  The learning curve goes from absurd to insane though as far as achieving deftness goes since evil requires knowing vi to make use of, and utilizing the emacs features requires knowing emacs.  What's sweet about the set up though is that you gain access to emacs lisp, multithreading, better integration with other gnu programs like gdb and gcc, and major modes like org mode that are brilliant.  I don't recommend that anyone do this, but I think it is state of the art as far as editors go due to combining the strengths of the emacs platform with vim's superior modal editing design and better micro-optimization of frequently used tasks.  Evil is pretty impressive though due to how rapidly the development has been.  The documentation for it is absolutely atrocious though and requires reading the source code to determine what commands are used so that you can rebind some things.  Like I said though, I don't recommend doing things this way for other humans.  I don't think that evil has a parallel to vim's autocommands though, which I used in vim for various things.  There is probably an emacsian way to achieve that however.  I think it's a shame that normal people who could benefit from well designed programs (not necessarily emacs or vim here) won't ever do so due to being unwilling to invest the time in learning them.  I use matlab/mathematica everyday but most people are stuck with calculators.</div>
			
		<hr />
	</div>
</div>Alright, I am going to say something that I think most of you will disagree with, but the more I use VIM/Evil and research it, find great resources the more I consider VIM very easy to gain great proficiency in.  I was hesitant to say this before, but after reading Drew Neil's <i>Practical VIM</i> he does such an excellent job of informing the readers of all the features and the various editor paradigms that it is super trivial to access and become adept at these insanely powerful features that no other editor has.  I think it's kind of boneheaded to not use EVIL or VIM at this point if you write a lot of papers/programs now.  Beforehand I thought the learning curve was madness, but it's really not.  Why? While VIM has an incredibly powerful and nuanced system in place with many individual key maps, pretty much in all cases those key maps have a pattern about them that you can chain together, and this is consistent through out, so the material you have to learn is very small.  Emacs is kind of a cluster fuck, but VIM/EVIL is really terse and excellently designed.  I went though the Practical VIM book that Neil wrote, and EVIL surpisingly already has a great deal of the VIM features implemented, even some of the advanced ones.  The things not supported though you have Emacs alternatives for in various ways, so I think this is an exceptional utility to learn, and it will really save your hands.  I consider it one of the best expenditures of time to learn ever, and I use it every day.  I use Emacs as my primary editor now, but learning VIM's concepts let me go straight into EVIL without losing speed really.  I'm still absorbing Emacs stuff, which I am finding very nontrivial to grok, but it's super powerful.  The main thing is I need to microoptimize the layouts more and become more proficient at elisp etc.  <br />
<br />
Anyways, here is my suggestions for becoming pro at VIM and improving your life forever.<br />
1) Do vimtutor <br />
2) Watch vimcasts and follow along<br />
3) Read Practical VIM<br />
4) Use it for all of your editing so that using all the features is seamless<br />
<br />
Even just after doing the first step you will likely be way faster than your previous methodology.  After doing the other 2 you will be pro.  I did watch all of Derek Wyatt's videos but I don't consider them worth doing now due to the awesome stuff pointed out in those (like Ctrl-O for doing one Normal mode action while in Insert mode) is covered in a much terser format in Neil's book.  I cannot hype it enough; it is one of the best technical books I have ever read and opened my eyes to some things I had overlooked like the expression register in VIM (EVIL does not have this sadly, but emacs has it covered in other ways).  I bought the book for some of my nerdier friends who are more willing to invest in learning new skills and they have all loved it.  <br />
<br />
The more GUI obsessed nerds are not down for learning this at all though, so they cannot be helped.  Emacs is awesome though, but is brutal and not as well documented or accessible as VIM is, so it's harder to grasp but it is much more powerful, especially once you add EVIL to the mix.  It's an unstoppable combo and state of the art IMO.  Elisp, org mode, micro optimization, EVIL, autocomplete, development for all languages which is especially useful for those that have shoddy IDEs still, snippets, refactoring, multithreaded, great toolchain for development, comint/slime, it's perfect and amazing.  The best program of all time IMO, especially on UNIX.  I'm loving it.  I would like to add in some pedals and a different keyboard into the mix, but I solely use my laptop and I work in different spots so it is not worth carrying all the extra baggage for me.</blockquote>
