		<div class="title">Re: Ubuntu Unity</div>
	
	<div class="content">
		<blockquote class="restore">I redact my previous comment about VIM's expression register and EMACS.  It turns out that EMACS has quite an exceptional complement (even better perhaps, I certainly think so) to VIM's expression register feature.  EMACS has a built-in calculator (M-x calc) that is capable of quite advanced things, even complicated tasks like taking derivatives, integrals, solving a set of linear equations, and matrices.  The calculator uses the superior RPN too, so infix notation is avoided (infix is complete shit but I digress).  And EVIL supports dumping the literal contents of a register into the current point in the buffer.  Also, I found out recently that Org Mobile is supported and developed for Android, but there is no up to date equivalent for iOS which sucks a lot as Org Mode is brilliantly done, and being able to use that without having to break out a laptop would be panty dropping greatness.<br />
<br />
For cool examples of emacs calc see: <br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.masteringemacs.org/articles/2012/04/25/fun-emacs-calc/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.masteringemacs.org/articl...un-emacs-calc/</a><br />
<a href="http://www.linuxjournal.com/article/5873" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.linuxjournal.com/article/5873</a><br />
<a href="http://www.linuxjournal.com/article/6306" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.linuxjournal.com/article/6306</a></blockquote>
