		<div class="datetime">October 19th, 2012, 02:45 AM</div>
		<span class="username">MI Redeux</span>
	</div>
	
	
		<div class="title">Re: Ubuntu Unity</div>
	
	<div class="content">
		<blockquote class="restore">It's really nice being able to use emacs for everything.  Even niche or new languages that do not have a good IDE for them work well in the emacs environment.  For example, Scala and GO are well supported by emacs packages.  I don't think emacs is nearly as nice for writing programs for microcontrollers though.  As the IDE we used in my microprocessor class I had when doing my BSEE was very nice.  You could see the values of registers, stack, stack pointer, ports, the different memory addresses, etc. all in one window.  The text editor was really shit but everything else was so nice that it made up for it.  If you do disassembly IDA Pro is too nice to pass up though, but for the majority of cases emacs is exceptional, a great tool for sure.  I wish it was not impossibly steep to learn though as it could help a lot of people.</blockquote>
	</div>
</li>
</ul>


